<br />
The 4-strength symbols tend to get screwed royally by the figure exchange tile. So I like to draw into those late as trump cards (or hopefully draw into them after everyone has played their figure exchange tiles). <br />
<br />
I tried a strategy playing with all the ships in my opening hand and that was a disaster. I played them all right away (to secure cities and double village harbours) but I found I really need a ship or two later on in the game. <br />
<br />
Finally I settled on using Samurai ONLY in my opening hand. This way, i&#39;m totally immune to Figure Exchange and can make a strong play for Edo. So I tried:<br />
<br />
3 Samurai<br />
2 Samurai<br />
2 Samurai<br />
1 Samurai<br />
1 Ronin<br />
<br />
I was debating on starting with the Ronin versus another 1 Samurai. But drawing into the Ronin as you last tile (or close to the end) is a disaster. I find it to be the best game piece there is. And there will be 2-3 moments in the game where you can use a Ronin to great effect. I like having it from the beginning so that I never miss the opportunity. I used it last night to score FOUR figures in one turn! WOW.<br />
<br />
So I think this is my new favourite opening hand. Very strong, extremely versatile. Note that you should be going for ties in the mid-late game since you run out of versatility later on and might need to finish the game quickly.  <br><BR><font size=1>09:49 11-02-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#A2B1C1>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>The Bolshieviks</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont"><img src=http://www.capitollegends.com/images/nikolaivolkoff150x150.jpg><br />
<br />
<br />
<b>YOU VILL LOSE THE TWILIGHT STRUGGLE, COMRADE!</b> <br><BR><font size=1>14:56 11-01-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">The reviews are off the charts. I very much expect to get it for XMAS. It&#39;s in all the stores now (they must have reprinted it or something). I can&#39;t wait :) <br><BR><font size=1>14:47 11-01-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#A2B1C1>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Shewski</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">Twilight Struggle is tremendous.  Card driven, sort of like Battlelore, but the cards are either Us/USSR/both.  So a lot of the game is in maximizing the crappy cards you get (ie springing a USSR card when it won&#39;t really affect you as the US player). <br><BR><font size=1>14:34 11-01-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">I hate the switcheroo piece. I have no idea how to use it properly. Ronin is obvious to use when you can get 2 pieces. But the switcheroo really mixes me up. <br />
