<br />
It usually comes down to someone making a great switcheroo at the end for a triple. <br><BR><font size=1>10:08 11-01-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">Hey so Samurai is really fun. It&#39;s the first 45-minute board game I&#39;ve played in decades. Very fast, very lite, very easy yet deep. Light on the strategy, heavy on the tactics. Lots of fun. I like it. Picking a starting hand is VERY CCG-like. Good fun.  <br><BR><font size=1>09:35 11-01-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#A2B1C1>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">just got done reading the Samurai rules. It&#39;s a tile placement game and sounds seriously fun. <br />
<br />
You have 25 tiles or so to place throughout the game but, here&#39;s one of the cool features, you get to pick 5 of them to start with. This plays out similar to deck construction since the 5 you pick will influence your strategy for the game. <br />
<br />
Many seasoned players get used to having favourites and end up picking the same 5 time and time again, so they play a variant where your starting &#39;hand&#39; of 5 tiles is completely random. Sounds like fun too. I think the first game we play will be a random 5 tile start since we don&#39;t know what any of the tiles really do... yet.<br />
<br />
<br />
